PrepAI – AI-Powered Interview Intelligence Tool
What It Is
PrepAI is a web application where a user pastes any job posting URL and receives a fully personalized interview preparation kit within seconds. Instead of spending hours manually reading a job description and guessing what to study, the tool does the research automatically and hands you a structured, prioritized prep plan.

How It Works (User Flow)
The experience is intentionally two-step and frictionless.
Step 1 — Input. The user lands on a minimal home screen with a single input bar. They paste a job URL (from LinkedIn, Greenhouse, Lever, Workday, or any job board) and click Analyze. A short scanning animation plays while the backend processes the posting — this gives the user feedback that something real is happening rather than an instant page swap.
Step 2 — Results Dashboard. The app transitions to a split dashboard. Everything the user needs to prepare is now organized in one view, broken into a sidebar and a main panel.

What the Dashboard Shows
The Sidebar (Role Intelligence)
The left panel gives a quick snapshot of the role. It shows the job title and company at the top, then a row of skill tags — these are the actual technologies and concepts extracted from the job description, color-coded to distinguish core requirements (highlighted in green) from secondary or preferred qualifications (dimmer, grey). Below that is a topic breakdown: a simple bar chart showing the relative weight of each domain in the posting. For the Capital One example, LLM Systems and ML Infrastructure score high, Cloud scores medium, and Behavioral scores low. This tells the user immediately where to invest their prep time.
The Main Panel (Questions)
The main area is where the real value lives. Questions are organized into three tabs — Technical, System Design, and Behavioral — so the user can focus on one category at a time.
Each question is displayed as a card showing the question text, a difficulty badge (Hard / Medium / Easy), and the specific topic it maps to from the job description. When the user clicks a card, it expands to reveal a hint — a short list of keywords, frameworks, and concepts they should weave into their answer. This is not a model answer; it is a guided nudge so the user can practice recall rather than passive reading.

The Core Value Proposition
The key insight behind the project is that most interview prep is wasted on generic content. A candidate studying for a Capital One Senior AI Engineer role should not be reviewing the same generic "tell me about yourself" material as someone applying to a junior data analyst role. PrepAI makes the prep specific to the exact posting, using the language of that company, the stack they mentioned, and the soft skills they called out in the description.
For instance, the Capital One JD explicitly mentions "resilient trail blazer" and "clarity to big, undefined problems" — PrepAI picks that up and generates a behavioral question that directly targets those phrases, with a hint telling the candidate why that question was chosen.

What Makes It a Strong Portfolio Project
From a technical standpoint the project touches several meaningful areas. It requires web scraping to pull raw job posting content, NLP to extract and categorize skills and topics from unstructured text, LLM prompt engineering to generate relevant questions from the extracted content, and a clean frontend to make it usable. That combination — scraping, NLP, LLM orchestration, and UI — covers the full stack of a modern AI product.
From a presentation standpoint it is immediately understandable to anyone who has ever applied for a job, which means a recruiter can grasp the value in under ten seconds. It is also easy to demo live in an interview, which is a significant advantage over a notebook-based project.

What It Is Not (Scope Boundaries for V1)
To keep the first version focused and shippable, PrepAI does not include user accounts, saved sessions, a quiz/scoring mode, resume comparison, or company research beyond the job posting itself. Those are all logical next features, but the core loop — URL in, prep kit out — is complete and valuable on its own.